But the acceptance of that suggestion would necessitate the difficult explanation of why P and ΜΕ have quos where MF has quod, and voco where ΜΕ has vocabo vocabo for the usual vocabo. ΜΕ, together with ME, Ρ, OG, MD, has solicet deum where OD and the other manuscripts have Mum scilicet. This latter variant, however, is non-determinative. OD, ΜΕ, MF, P, ΟΟ, OG, MD, are brought together by their use of Factum for Item foetam. FOLIOS 161-162b

For this passage thirty-nine manuscripts have been collated. As in the passage on fs. 33th the larger groups may be denoted by (Ι), (ΙΙ), (ΙΙΙ),

-- with the arrangement as follows: (I) OB, OM, MA, ΜΒ, MD, ΜΙ, CM,

LC, LF, LG, HA, W; (ΙΙ) ΟΟ, OF, OG, ΜΕ, ΜΟ, ΜΗ, MK, CA, CB, CC, CF, CH, LB, LD, LE, LT, ΗΒ, Χ; (ΙΙΙ) OA, ΟΕ, ΜΟ, LA, OD, ML, MF, Ρ, Υ. (Ι) breaks up into (OB, LF, LG), (OM, MA, ΜΒ, MD, ΜΙ, CM, LC, HA, W), (MA, ΜΒ, MD, ΜΙ, ΟΜ, LC), (OM, HA, W), (MA, MD), (ΜΙ, CM, LC), (ΟΜ, HA), with MD again showing the influence of corrections from another line in its exemplar. (II) contains the smaller groups (OF, ΜΕ, ΜΟ, ΜΗ, MK, CB, ΟΟ, LB, ΗΒ), (ΜΕ, ΜΗ, ΟΟ, LB), (OF, MG), (CB, ΗΒ), (CA, X), (CF, ΕΤ), (ΟΟ, OG—first part).
